<div class="two-col">
  <div
    class="key-box"
    style="background:#f0f8f0;border:2px solid var(--green)"
  >
    <div class="key-title" style="color:var(--green)">
      Oxidized DBI (colored) — photostable
    </div>
    <div class="key-body">
      The fully intact C=C chromophore creates an efficient system for
      handling incoming photons. Wavelengths in the orange-red range are
      absorbed and their energy is dissipated as heat — harmlessly, without
      breaking any bonds. The blue-violet wavelengths that create the color
      are reflected back to the eye before they penetrate the molecule at all.
      <br/>
      <br/>
      Neither absorbed nor reflected photons reach the C–Br bond with
      sufficient energy to break it. The color itself acts as a shield for the
      bromine.
      <br/>
      <br/>
      <b>Result: bromine protected. Cannot be debrominated by UV.</b>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div
    class="key-box"
    style="background:#fff8e8;border:2px solid var(--gold)"
  >
    <div class="key-title" style="color:#7a6010">
      Leuco DBI (colorless) — photolabile
    </div>
    <div class="key-body">
      The C=C has been broken. The extended conjugation that made the molecule
      an efficient photon-handler is disrupted. The molecule is now colorless
      and transparent — it neither absorbs nor reflects the UV range.
      <br/>
      <br/>
      UV photons pass through the colorless liquid solution intact, reaching
      the C–Br bond directly. The bond breaks. Bromine departs as a bromide
      ion (Br⁻). This is permanent — the C–Br bond is destroyed, not
      temporarily disrupted.
      <br/>
      <br/>
      <b>Result: bromine vulnerable. Debromination occurs rapidly.</b>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
